  "base_commit": "e606eb81a86232c5adf35579d5b61b317d474ca1",
  "pr_number": 2820,
  "issue_number": 2818,
  "issue_title": "fix(parser): generalize \"as long as enchanted creature is X, it gets\u2026/has\u2026\" inverted-grant beyond Legendary (CR 613/611.3a)",
  "issue_body": "Closes #2674 (Shield of the Oversoul does nothing on its enchanted creature).\n\n## Summary\n\nAuras (and Equipment) of the form **\"As long as enchanted/equipped creature is `<characteristic>`, it gets `<P/T>` and has `<keyword>`\"** only resolve correctly when the characteristic is the literal word **`legendary`**. For every other characteristic \u2014 a **color** (\"is white\" / \"is green\"), a card **type/subtype**, or the **basic** supertype \u2014 the buff silently lands on the **Aura itself** instead of the enchanted creature, so the creature gets nothing.\n\nThis is a single-card special case wearing a class handler's name: the inverted-grant parser calls `parse_attached_subject_is_legendary`, which hardcodes `tag(\"creature is legendary\")`. The fix replaces that hardcoded qualifier with the parser's existing general predicate-tail building block so the whole class is covered.\n\n## The card class (build for the class, not the card)\n\nPattern: **`As long as enchanted <subject> is <characteristic>, it gets <pt> and has <keyword>.`** (and the `equipped` / Equipment variant).\n\n- **Shield of the Oversoul** \u2014 \"As long as enchanted creature is **white**, it gets +1/+1 and has flying. / As long as enchanted creature is **green**, it gets +1/+1 and has indestructible.\" (the reported card; color-conditional)\n- The general form covers any future Aura whose conditional grant keys on the host's color, type, subtype, or supertype \u2014 not just `legendary`.\n\nCR references (verified against `docs/MagicCompRules.txt`):\n- **CR 611.3a** \u2014 a continuous effect whose duration/condition is \"as long as \u2026\" only applies while the condition holds.\n- **CR 613.x** \u2014 layer system; the grant (P/T in layer 7c, abilities in layer 6) applies to the **enchanted creature**, the object named by \"it\".\n- **CR 105.2b / 105.4** \u2014 a multicolored object *is* each of its colors, so a green-white creature satisfies both \"is white\" and \"is green\". (The runtime already honors this \u2014 `FilterProp::HasColor` uses `.contains(color)` in `game/filter.rs`; the bug is purely in the parser path, not color evaluation.)\n\n## Root cause (verified in current `main`)\n\nParsing `\"As long as enchanted creature is white, it gets +1/+1 and has flying.\"` today produces:\n\n```text\nStaticDefinition {\n    affected: Some(SelfRef),                       // \u2190 WRONG: the Aura, not the host\n    modifications: [AddPower 1, AddToughness 1, AddKeyword Flying],\n    condition: Some(IsPresent { filter: creature + EnchantedBy + HasColor{White} }),\n}\n```\n\n`affected: SelfRef` is the Aura enchantment (not a creature), so the +1/+1/flying buff is applied to the Aura and the enchanted creature is unaffected \u2014 it \"doesn't do anything, still gets destroyed, doesn't give flying\" (exactly the #2674 report).\n\nCompare the **working** `legendary` case, which yields the correct shape:\n\n```text\nStaticDefinition {\n    affected: Some(Typed(creature + EnchantedBy + HasSupertype{Legendary})),  // \u2190 buff lands on the host\n    modifications: [AddPower 1, AddToughness 1, AddKeyword Ward{1}],\n    condition: None,                               // qualifier folded into the affected filter\n}\n```\n\nThe divergence is in **`crates/engine/src/parser/oracle_static/shared.rs`**:\n\n- `try_parse_inverted_attached_subject_grant` (\u2248line 269) calls `parse_attached_subject_is_legendary` to derive the `affected` filter.\n- `parse_attached_subject_is_legendary` (\u2248line 284) hardcodes `nom_tag_tp(&rest, \"creature is legendary\")` \u2192 returns `creature + EnchantedBy + HasSupertype{Legendary}` and **`None` for anything else**.\n- When it returns `None`, the line falls through to the generic inverted \"As long as `<cond>`, `<effect>`\" rewrite, which keeps `affected = SelfRef` and attaches the qualifier as a presence `condition` \u2014 correct for source-referential statics, wrong for an attached-subject grant where \"it\" = the host.\n\nThe notable smell: the parser **already builds the exact right filter** (`creature + EnchantedBy + HasColor{White}`) \u2014 it's sitting inside the presence `condition`. It just isn't promoted to `affected`.\n\n## Fix\n\nGeneralize the attached-subject qualifier parser to reuse the existing predicate-tail building block instead of the `legendary`-only literal.\n\n1. **Reuse, don't reimplement.** `crates/engine/src/parser/oracle_nom/condition.rs::parse_bare_predicate_tail` (\u2248line 614) already parses a copula predicate tail (`is <X>`) into a `TargetFilter::Typed` carrying the predicate's own props \u2014 **color \u2192 `HasColor`**, legendary/basic \u2192 `HasSupertype`, type/subtype \u2192 `parse_type_phrase`. The attached-subject merge at condition.rs \u2248590-602 already folds such a predicate into the `EnchantedBy` subject filter.\n2. **Rename + generalize** `parse_attached_subject_is_legendary` \u2192 `parse_attached_subject_qualifier`: after stripping the `enchanted `/`equipped ` attachment prefix and `creature is `, parse the remaining characteristic via the shared predicate-tail parser, then return `Typed(creature + {EnchantedBy|EquippedBy} + <predicate props>)`. The `legendary` case becomes one instance of the general path (output preserved byte-for-byte).\n3. Result: the color/type/subtype/supertype variants take the **same** correct branch \u2014 `affected` = the enchanted creature with the qualifier folded in, `condition = None` \u2014 so the buff lands on the host whenever the host matches.\n\nThis is a pure parser change: no new effect, no new enum variant, no runtime change. It deletes a special case and routes the class through machinery the codebase already trusts (nom-combinator mandate satisfied \u2014 no new string dispatch).\n\n## Verification plan\n\n- `cargo fmt --all`; parser-combinator gate (`scripts/check-parser-combinators.sh`); engine lib suite.\n- Parser tests at the building-block level (extend `oracle_static/tests.rs` alongside the existing `static_as_long_as_enchanted_creature_is_legendary_grants_to_enchanted_creature`):\n  - **color**: `\"As long as enchanted creature is white, it gets +1/+1 and has flying.\"` \u2192 `affected = Typed(creature + EnchantedBy + HasColor{White})`, `condition = None`, mods `[AddPower 1, AddToughness 1, AddKeyword Flying]`.\n  - **second color line** (Shield's green clause) \u2192 `HasColor{Green}` + `Indestructible`.\n  - **regression**: the `legendary` case is unchanged (still `HasSupertype{Legendary}`, `condition = None`).\n  - **type/subtype**: `\"As long as enchanted creature is an artifact, it gets +1/+1.\"` folds the type into the affected filter.\n  - **equipped variant**: same shape with `EquippedBy`.\n- End-to-end (engine): an Aura granting \"as long as enchanted creature is white, it gets +1/+1 and has flying\" on a **multicolored** (G/W) host grants +1/+1 and flying (and the green clause grants indestructible), confirming `HasColor.contains` multicolor membership flows through. The earlier `SelfRef` mis-binding produced no host change.\n\nLocal toolchain: tests run via `cargo +nightly-2026-04-19-x86_64-pc-windows-gnu test -p engine --lib` with mingw `dlltool` on PATH (Tilt is down in this clone). The bug and both parse shapes above were verified by dumping `parse_oracle_text` output for Shield of the Oversoul against current `main`.",
